{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536931"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.02,0.52,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111994"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8530"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1490"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44429"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111994"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two week history of lower abdominal and pelvic pain. The pain is constant, dull in nature, and worse with movement. She reports having had unprotected sex about a month prior. She has never had a sexually transmitted infection before. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with one regular partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her temperature is 37.2\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the lower abdomen and mild cervical motion tenderness on vaginal examination. There is a white cervical discharge seen from the cervix and in the vagina.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High vaginal swabs","Urine MCS","Endocervical swabs","Low vaginal swabs","Pelvic ultrasound scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), including lower abdominal pain, cervical motion tenderness, and cervical discharge. The history of unprotected sexual intercourse increases the likelihood of a sexually transmitted infection as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocervical swabs\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate initial investigation to confirm the diagnosis of PID. These swabs are specifically designed to collect samples from the endocervical canal, which is the optimal site for detecting \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E - the two most common causative organisms of PID. Modern nucleic acid amplification tests (NAATs) performed on endocervical swabs have high sensitivity and specificity for these pathogens. Obtaining these samples before starting antibiotics is crucial for accurate microbiological diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh vaginal swabs\u003C/strong\u003E are more appropriate for diagnosing conditions such as bacterial vaginosis, candidiasis, or trichomoniasis. While these infections can co-exist with PID, they are not the primary causative organisms of PID and therefore high vaginal swabs are not the optimal first-line investigation for suspected PID.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy, culture, and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E (MCS) is useful for diagnosing urinary tract infections but has limited value in diagnosing PID. While first-void urine can be used for NAAT testing for chlamydia and gonorrhoea this needs to be specifically requested as a urine PCR not urine MCS and patients should be asked to collect a first-void sample not a mid-stream sample that is usually collected in urine MCS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow vaginal swabs\u003C/strong\u003E are typically used to detect organisms colonizing the lower genital tract, such as Group B Streptococcus in pregnant women. They are not the optimal sample for diagnosing the upper genital tract infection characteristic of PID.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in complicated cases of PID to identify tubo-ovarian abscesses or hydrosalpinx, but it is not the most appropriate initial investigation. Ultrasound findings are often normal in early or mild PID, and the diagnosis remains primarily clinical, supported by microbiological evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining endocervical swabs, empiric antibiotic therapy should be initiated promptly to cover the likely pathogens, including \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E, and anaerobes. Partner notification and treatment are also essential components of management to prevent reinfection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endocervical swabs are essential for detecting Neisseria gonorrhoeae and Chlamydia trachomatis, the most common causative organisms of pelvic inflammatory disease.","Clinical diagnosis of pelvic inflammatory disease requires cervical motion tenderness, lower abdominal pain, and often cervical discharge.","Appropriate sampling for microbiological testing should be performed before initiating empiric antibiotic therapy for pelvic inflammatory disease."],"references":["Brunham RC, Gottlieb SL, Paavonen J. Pelvic inflammatory disease. New England Journal of Medicine. 2015 May 21;372(21):2039-48. Available online at ; https://nuhem.com/emlinks/LLSA%20Articles%202018/Pelvic%20Inflammatory%20Disease.pdf","Curry A, Williams T, Penny ML. Pelvic inflammatory disease: diagnosis, management, and prevention. American family physician. 2019 Sep 15;100(6):357-64. Available online at ; https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2019/0915/p357.pdf","Empirical therapy for non-severe Pelvic Inflammatory disease [published 2019 April]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed (18/11/2024)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94058"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-22T21:26:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T21:26:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8530"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111994"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"gr